title: For Sale:  Beeman P1 air Handgun, .177 caliber, used
location: South of OKC, Oklahoma City, Oklahoma
postcontent:
This is a used, but in excellent condiion Beeman P1 air handgun in .177 caliber.  These go for up to $459.00 new.  Excellent shooter.  Has Hogue 1911 rubber finger grip.  Below is description from Beeman.  Need to sell for money for a gun project.  Will sell for $175.

Looks like a .45 1911 firearm...and just as accurate! Made in Germany by the legendary Weihrauch company, the Beeman P1 is considered by many to be the Holy Grail of air pistols. This is an heirloom airgun that you'll pass along to your grandchildren and beyond.

The gun's heft and balance convey quality and substance. It fills your hand without feeling bulky or oversized. The unusual overlever cocking mechanism compresses the powerful mainspring, and the hammer is actually the catch for it. Highly adjustable two-stage trigger, which has a serrated surface for more control, will help you extract maximum accuracy from the P1. In fact, the adjustable trigger is so crisp, you'll wish it was on your firearms.

The dovetail grooves are extra wide, and our accessory list has several 11mm to 14mm mounts that are known to fit.

Unlike many modern air pistols, the P1 isn't made of molded synthetics. It's a solid metal gun with finely checkered walnut grips. And, it's ambidextrous. The 11mm dovetails make it easy to mount a pistol scope or a red dot sight.

The P1 has two power levels. The different power levels are created by cocking the gun to different lock points. See the detail shots to see how to cock the gun for high power and low power.

The distance you shoot, the weight of the pellet and the type of target will let you determine which power level is best. The P1 is an excellent indoor trainer for those who shoot the M1911A1.

postcontent:
Sellier & Bellot (European brand primers- they make good ammo) one brick minus 100 primers (900 primers) I bought these last weekend at the local gun show. I loaded one tray of 100 in 40 cal for my competition Glock 35 which has a light aftermarket striker spring (Wolff) for a better trigger pull. I experienced about a 20% failure rate of light strikes so these aren't gonna work for me. (most did fire the second time I ran them thru the pistol so I know there's nothing wrong with the primers)

Just did a little more research and these may actually be small rifle primers and not SPP.  Which would explain the SR on the box despite it saying "Rifle, Pistol and Revolver" in the top right corner. Plus the ammo I loaded with these felt a little hotter and ran about 50fps faster than the same load with Federal pistol primers on my chronograph.. Perfect for loading some .223 for an AR-15.

Mike

title: For Sale/Trade:  Reminder regarding .22LR prices
location: North Carolina, North Carolina, United States
postcontent:
I can't help but notice that the aftermarket asking price for .22 ammo seems to be a little misleading and that people would have you believe that they, themselves, paid a hefty price for ammunition just before they sold their gun leaving them without a need for their ammo, and they just need to get rid of it at a little higher price than they paid.  Heck, I'll just say it: some people on here are liars.

If you've posted an ad like the ones I am talking about and this hits close to home for you, don't worry, you are not alone in your untruthful posts.  Instead of saying, "I have $.10 per round in these and I sold my gun and just want to recoup my expenses," perhaps you would get less ill wishes from the people on this board by saying something more like, "I bought this ammo when it was available, knowing all along I would be wanting to/willing to sell it at a profit."  At least then I could respect you.

So, since the 'asking price' on sites like this often skew the perception of what ammo is worth or what it costs, I've created a small list of some of the more common types of 22LR so that the people who just don't ever seem to find any in stores can at least know the base prices that the seller paid.  For instance, before you consider paying $.10 per round of Federal 550 (red box, which is a Wal-Mart exclusive item, by the way) totaling $55, keep in mind that Wal-Mart sells them for just under $25.  Your paying double will only encourage them to take it from the shelf again the next time they see it.  [Note: I am indifferent to gun shops who charge $25 for 100xMiniMags, ONLY because they rent guns and insist that you use their ammo in those guns. The $25 makes sure they will have it available when you rent, so... it sucks as a buyer, but I can understand.]

The prices are based on Gander Mountain (GM) and Wal-Mart (WM).  To be fair, I will use the higher of the two if they both carry them.

Federal 550 (red box) ...$25 (WM exclusive)
Federal 525 Champion (blue box) ...$25
American Eagle (40) ...$3 (Dick's)
CCI
	Blazer (50) ...$3
	MiniMag (100) ...$8
	Stinger (50) ...$8 (may have been lowered to $6.99)
	Velocitor (50) ...$8
	Standard Velotity (50) ...$5
	Standard Velocity (100) ...$7.47 (black box, new at Wal-Mart; as expected, this one has already popped up here for $12)
Remington
	Thunderbolt (50) ...$3
	SubSonic (100) ...$8
	Standard Velocity/Target (50) ...$5
	Bucket O' Bullets (1400) ...$60-73
	Golden Bullets (225) ...$13
	Golden Bullets (525) ...$25
Winchester
	222 bulk ...$13
	Super-X (100) ...$8
RWS Target Rifle (50) ...$8 (German, fantastic stuff)

As you can see, outside the RWS, CCI Stinger/Velocitor/Standard, and most of the Eley stuff, basically nothing costs more than $.08 per round.  Many, perhaps most, of us know this and just roll our eyes at these ridiculous asking prices by gougers.  This list is meant for the benefit of people who don't ever come across them in stores and so don't know what the current retail market is for the stuff.

(Anyone still wanting to pay $.10, .12, .14+ per round should send me a text. I like free money, too.)
